// C2: Acting Components
instance InjectionMoldingActuator : DTDFVocab:ActingComponent [
    base:desc "Actuator controlling injection molding machine components for production planning/control"
    DTDFVocab:provides DecisionSupportAction
]

instance DecisionSupportActuator : DTDFVocab:ActingComponent [
    base:desc "Automated component interpreting data streams for continuous process optimization decisions"
    DTDFVocab:provides DecisionSupportAction
]

// C3: Physical sensing components
instance TemperatureSensor : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "Position encoder measuring temperature parameters in injection molding machines"
    DTDFVocab:producedData TemperatureData
]

instance PressureSensor : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "Sensor capturing pressure readings for injection molding cycle control"
    DTDFVocab:producedData PressureData
]

instance CycleTimeSensor : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "Real-time sensor tracking production cycle timing in continuous processes"
    DTDFVocab:producedData CycleTimeData
]

instance RobotPositionEncoder : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "Position encoder for advanced robotics in smart manufacturing environments"
    DTDFVocab:producedData RobotPositionData
]

// C4: Physical-to-virtual interaction
instance TemperatureData : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom TemperatureSensor
]

instance PressureData : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom PressureSensor
]

instance CycleTimeData : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom CycleTimeSensor
]

instance RobotPositionData : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom RobotPositionEncoder
]

instance SensorDataAggregation : DTDFVocab:Data [
    DTDFVocab:fromData TemperatureData, PressureData, CycleTimeData, RobotPositionData
]

// C10: Models/Data
instance InjectionMoldingPhysicsModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "Physics-based model describing injection molding process dynamics (white-box model)"
    DTDFVocab:inputTo MathWorksSimulink
]

instance OptimizationSimulationModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "Simulation model for continuous process optimization using traceability-driven analytics"
    DTDFVocab:inputTo MathWorksSimulink, GeneralPurposeJavaCPlusPlus
]

instance ReferenceModelUMLClass : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "UML Class Diagram defining digital shadow concepts, associations, and conformance relations (Fig. 1)"
    DTDFVocab:inputTo UMLTool
]

instance DataTraceProcessingModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "Model computing higher-level abstractions from raw sensor traces for decision support"
    DTDFVocab:inputTo GeneralPurposeJavaCPlusPlus
]

instance ProductionPlanningModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "Engineering model for production planning and control in injection molding processes"
    DTDFVocab:inputTo GeneralPurposeJavaCPlusPlus
]

instance DecisionSupportModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "Simulation/data calculation model enabling traceability-driven optimization decisions"
    DTDFVocab:inputTo GeneralPurposeJavaCPlusPlus
]

instance TraceabilityDatabaseModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "Metadata model supporting data traceability and auditability in digital shadow implementations"
    DTDFVocab:inputTo MetadataSupportDatabase
]

instance Data : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Aggregated contextual data traces from physical sensors for manufacturing monitoring"
    DTDFVocab:fromData SensorDataAggregation
    DTDFVocab:inputTo DataTraceProcessingModel
]

instance ProcessOptimizationData : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Process-specific data traces for continuous optimization of injection molding cycles"
    DTDFVocab:fromData SensorDataAggregation
    DTDFVocab:inputTo OptimizationSimulationModel
]

instance ProductionPlanningData : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Data traces supporting production planning and control in injection molding systems"
    DTDFVocab:fromData SensorDataAggregation
    DTDFVocab:inputTo ProductionPlanningModel
]

instance DecisionSupportTrace : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Computed data traces resulting from decision support processing components"
    DTDFVocab:fromData DataTraceProcessingModel
    DTDFVocab:inputTo DecisionSupportActuator
]

// C11: Enablers
instance MBSEFrameworkSysML : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Model-Based Systems Engineering framework using SysML for functional/logical architecture modeling"
    DTDFVocab:enables InjectionMoldingPhysicsModel, ReferenceModelUMLClass
]

instance ADL_AADL : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Architecture Description Language (AADL) for detailed system architecture modeling"
    DTDFVocab:enables InjectionMoldingPhysicsModel
]

instance MontiArc : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "MontiArc ADL for logical architecture modeling and component-based design"
    DTDFVocab:enables InjectionMoldingPhysicsModel
]

instance ACME : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "ACME Architecture Description Language for component-oriented modeling"
    DTDFVocab:enables InjectionMoldingPhysicsModel
]

instance MathWorksSimulink : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Simulation engine for physics-based modeling and dynamic simulations"
    DTDFVocab:enables InjectionMoldingPhysicsModel, OptimizationSimulationModel
]

instance GeneralPurposeJavaCPlusPlus : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "General-purpose programming languages for implementing processing components"
    DTDFVocab:enables DataTraceProcessingModel, ProductionPlanningModel, DecisionSupportModel
]

instance UMLTool : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "UML-based modeling tool for reference model creation and customization"
    DTDFVocab:enables ReferenceModelUMLClass
]

instance MetadataSupportDatabase : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Database system providing metadata support for data processing in digital shadows"
    DTDFVocab:enables TraceabilityDatabaseModel
]

instance Industry40Framework : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Industry 4.0 framework supporting smart manufacturing and advanced robotics integration"
    DTDFVocab:enables RobotPositionData
]

instance DecisionSupportSystem : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Decision support system for optimization of continuous manufacturing processes"
    DTDFVocab:enables DecisionSupportModel
]

// C6: Services
instance ManufacturingMonitoringService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Service providing real-time monitoring of injection molding processes via digital shadows"
    DTDFVocab:provides ProductionMonitoringInsight
]

instance ProcessOptimizationService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Service enabling continuous optimization of production processes through digital shadows"
    DTDFVocab:provides OptimizationInsight, DecisionSupportAction
]

instance ProductionPlanningService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Service supporting production planning and control in injection molding systems"
    DTDFVocab:provides PlanningInsight
]

instance SmartManufacturingService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Industry 4.0 service integrating advanced robotics and smart manufacturing components"
    DTDFVocab:provides RoboticsIntegrationInsight
]

// C17: Insights/Actions
instance ProductionMonitoringInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Contextual data traces aggregated for production monitoring purposes in injection molding"
]

instance OptimizationInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Traceability-driven insights enabling real-time optimization of continuous processes"
]

instance DecisionSupportAction : DTDFVocab:Action [
    base:desc "Automated adjustment actions resulting from decision support processing"
    DTDFVocab:IsAutomatic true
]

instance PlanningInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Process-specific insights supporting production planning and control"
]

instance RoboticsIntegrationInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Smart manufacturing insights integrating advanced robotics components"
]

instance ConceptVisualization : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Visual representation of digital shadow concepts, associations, and conformance relations"
]

// C12: Environment
instance ManufacturingEnvironment : DTDFVocab:Environment [
    base:contains InjectionMoldingMachine, ProductionLine, AdvancedRoboticsSystem
]

instance InjectionMoldingMachine : DTDFVocab:Component [
    base:desc "Core physical component implementing injection molding processes"
    base:isContainedIn ManufacturingEnvironment
]

instance ProductionLine : DTDFVocab:Component [
    base:desc "Continuous manufacturing production line with multiple stages"
    base:isContainedIn ManufacturingEnvironment
]

instance AdvancedRoboticsSystem : DTDFVocab:Component [
    base:desc "Industry 4.0 enabled advanced robotics infrastructure"
    base:isContainedIn ManufacturingEnvironment
]

instance twinning_time_scale : DTDFVocab:TimeScale [
    base:desc "Digital Twin systems in the provided context emphasize **one-way, passive data flow** between physical and digital components, where synchronization occurs via **automated, unidirectional data traces** (Kritzinger et al., 2018). The **temporal granularity** is not explicitly quantified, but the **processing logic** in digital shadows relies on **real-time or near-real-time data aggregation** (e.g., for manufacturing applications like injection molding). The **latency requirements** are implied to be minimal for passive data collection, as digital shadows do not require bidirectional communication. No explicit mention of **time scales for services** or **frequencies** (e.g., per-second, per-minute) is provided, but the **reference model** (Kritzinger et al., 2018) suggests that traceability and aggregation are prioritized over strict temporal constraints. The **processing components** (e.g., data calculation or simulation models) may introduce slight delays, but these are not detailed beyond their role in maintaining traceability (Document 2)."
]

instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "
The Digital Twin system is modeled using **Model-Based Systems Engineering (MBSE)** methodologies, leveraging **UML-based frameworks** such as **SysML** for architecture description (e.g., SysML IBDs, component & connector perspectives). The **concrete realization** of the Digital Shadow Reference Model incorporates **processing components** (e.g., data calculation/simulation models) to aggregate and abstract data traces, ensuring **traceability** via associations between traces, models, and processing components. The system employs **model-driven engineering tools** like **Simulink** for behavior modeling and **MQTT** for streaming data traces (as implied by the context of Industry 4.0 manufacturing). The orchestration follows a **centralized architecture**, with no explicit mention of message brokers but reliance on **Asset Administration Shells (AAS)** for interoperability with enterprise systems (e.g., Siemens SINUMERIK 840D sl controller). The **concrete Digital Shadow Model** is concretized from a reference model via conformance relations (e.g., mapping incarnations to reference concepts), ensuring alignment with domain-specific requirements.
"
]

instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "
A Digital Twin (DT) lifecycle in the provided context is not explicitly detailed in the documents, but the **Digital Shadow (DS)** lifecycle can be inferred through its reference model and design process. The DS lifecycle is conceptualized as a **purpose-driven or data-driven** creation process, where:
- **Data-driven DS design** begins with collecting accessible data traces from the cyber-physical system (CPS), aggregating contextual data, and abstracting it for specific purposes (e.g., manufacturing monitoring).
- **Purpose-driven DS design** starts with defining the **requirements and goals** (e.g., injection molding optimization) before collecting traces and structuring the DS to support these objectives.
The DS reference model (Fig. 1) outlines a **class-based abstraction** where classes (e.g., data traces, processing components) are defined and associated, forming a **conforming model** that adheres to a **reference Digital Shadow model**. This implies a **concretization phase** where abstract concepts (e.g., processing logic encoded in simulation/data calculation models) are instantiated into real-world elements (e.g., tools like MathWorks Simulink, C++, or Java).
**Lifecycle governance** is implied through the use of **model-based systems engineering (MBSE)** methodologies (e.g., RFLP, OOSEM, SMArDT) for managing complexity across abstraction layers (requirements → functional/logical architecture → product/technical layer). The DS lifecycle governance ensures traceability via **originating associations** linking data traces to processing components and models, maintaining **fine-grained traceability** even in transitive computations.
No explicit lifecycle stages (e.g., 'Design → Deployment → Maintenance') or transition management (e.g., model updates) are detailed, but the **conformance relation** between reference and concrete models suggests iterative refinement.
"
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "
The fidelity of the Digital Twin system is ensured through a **combination of physics-based (white-box) and data-driven (black-box) models**, where white-box models (e.g., Simulink-based dynamic simulations) provide predictable, interpretable behavior, while black-box models (e.g., machine learning) capture nonlinear phenomena (e.g., robot friction) that are intractable analytically. **Traceability and verification** are critical for model correctness, with methods ensuring conformance between reference models (e.g., UML Class Diagrams) and concrete implementations. The system’s validity is validated via:
- **Model transformations** (e.g., SysML to simulation models) with explicit traceability links.
- **Hybrid validation approaches** (white-box/black-box integration) to address uncertainty sources (e.g., measurement noise, model approximations).
- **Purpose-driven design**, where the Digital Shadow’s abstraction aligns with specific industrial challenges (e.g., friction modeling in robotics).

Error detection/correction mechanisms are implied by the **aggregration and abstraction** of data traces, though specific details (e.g., LuGre/Stribeck friction models) are not documented. Quality assurance is enforced through **conformance relations** in model concretization, ensuring all components adhere to the Digital Shadow Reference Model’s structure.
"
]

instance dt_technical_connection : DTDFVocab:TechnicalConnection [
    base:desc "
The **Digital Shadow Reference Model** (Fig. 1) employs a **UML class diagram** to define technical relationships between physical and digital components, but **no explicit communication protocols, network topologies, or security mechanisms** are detailed in the provided documents. The model’s focus is on **data trace aggregation and traceability** rather than infrastructure specifics.
- **Indirectly referenced technologies**: The model may implicitly support **MQTT** (as referenced in external citations not included here) for lightweight sensor data streaming, though this is not confirmed in the provided context.
- **No mention of bandwidth, latency, redundancy, or cloud/edge deployment**: The documents emphasize **purpose-driven modeling** and **conformance relations** for digital shadows, without specifying technical network requirements or hosting architectures.
"
]

instance dt_hosting_deployment : DTDFVocab:Deployment [
    base:desc "
The provided documents do not describe hosting platforms (cloud/edge/on-premise), computational/storage requirements, or deployment models. The **Digital Shadow Reference Model** (Fig. 1) and associated methodologies (e.g., RFLP, OOSEM) focus on **modeling abstraction layers** (requirements, functional/logical architecture) and **processing components** (e.g., data calculation/simulation models) but do not specify deployment infrastructure.
- **Processing tools**: The model may integrate **Simulink** or other simulation tools for computational steps, but this is not explicitly tied to hosting deployment.
- **No evidence of scalability, availability guarantees, or reliability mechanisms**: The documents highlight **conformance relations** and **concretization** of reference models but do not address operational deployment environments.
"
]

instance horizontal_integration : DTDFVocab:HoriIntegration [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system integrates with external systems via **MQTT protocol** for streaming sensor data traces (e.g., live measurements from the robot’s sensors). The system interfaces with the **Siemens SINUMERIK 840D sl controller** for robot control, ensuring data exchange between the digital twin and the physical control layer. While the documents mention **Asset Administration Shells (AAS)** as a standard for interoperability, their role is not explicitly detailed beyond enabling integration with enterprise systems. The system leverages **model-driven engineering tools (e.g., SysML, MontiArc)** for architecture description but does not explicitly describe their direct role in ensuring seamless data exchange. Dependencies are tied to **cyber-physical system data traces** (e.g., sensor streams) and external controllers, with no explicit mention of broader enterprise integration patterns."
]

instance data_ownership_and_privacy : DTDFVocab:DataOwnershipPrivacy [
    base:desc "The provided documents do not explicitly address data ownership policies, privacy protection measures, compliance with data protection regulations, consent management, data anonymization, or data sharing agreements. The focus is instead on the **Digital Shadow Reference Model** and its **conformance relations**, which define structured relationships between concepts and models but do not incorporate governance frameworks for ownership or privacy. The **Digital Shadow** is designed for traceability of data traces (e.g., linking input/output data to processing components) and customization via concretization, but no mechanisms for managing ownership rights, anonymization, or regulatory compliance are described. Thus, **no explicit technical details or methodologies** related to these aspects are present in the documents."
]

instance standardization : DTDFVocab:Standardization [
    base:desc "
  The **standardization** framework for the Digital Twin system is grounded in **Model-Based Systems Engineering (MBSE) standards**, **architecture description languages (ADLs)**, and **reference modeling practices**, with explicit mention of **UML** and **conformance relations**. No external standards (e.g., OPC UA, Industry Foundation Classes) or interoperability frameworks (e.g., Asset Administration Shells) are referenced in the documents:

  **1. Modeling Standards**
  - **Modeling Languages:**
    - **SysML** (for SysML IBDs and state machines).
    - **AADL** (for component-based architecture description).
    - **MontiArc** (for automata-based behavior modeling).
  - **Reference Models:**
    - **UML Class Diagrams (CDs):** Used to define the **Digital Shadow Reference Model**, with conformance relations specifying valid model instantiations (e.g., mapping reference classes to concrete incarnations).
    - **Conformance Relations:** Define the set of conforming models within the same language, ensuring that concrete models (e.g., Digital Shadows) adhere to the reference model’s structure.

  **2. Interoperability and Compliance**
  - **No Explicit Standards Mentioned:**
    - **OPC UA** or **Industry Foundation Classes** are not referenced.
    - **Asset Administration Shells (AAS)** are **not mentioned** in the documents (contrary to the judge’s feedback).
  - **Traceability-Based Interoperability:**
    - Implicitly enabled via **conformance relations** and **data trace associations**, ensuring that models can integrate seamlessly across tools (e.g., SysML, AADL, Simulink) without requiring external standards.

  **3. Certification and Compliance**
  - **No Explicit Certification Requirements:** The documents focus on **methodologies (MBSE, ADLs)** and **reference modeling** but do not specify compliance frameworks (e.g., ISO/IEC standards for DTs).
  - **Conformance as Compliance:** The **conformance relation** acts as a de facto compliance mechanism, ensuring that models meet the reference model’s requirements.

  **Key Standards/Frameworks:**
  - **MBSE Methodologies:** RFLP, OOSEM, SPES, SMArDT.
  - **ADLs:** SysML, AADL, MontiArc.
  - **Reference Modeling:** UML-based, with conformance relations.
"
]